"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 23–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-23-24.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/matthew.json (pre-existing: 23:1, 24:1)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch23 Seven Woes: phylacteries (tefillin) mechanics; tassels (tzitzit) from Num 15:38-40;
  whitewashed tombs before Passover from m. Maasrot Sheni 5:1 + b. Moed Katan 5a;
  Abel-to-Zechariah spans first to last martyr in the Hebrew canon (Gen 4 to 2 Chr 24:20-22);
  tithing of mint/dill/cummin from m. Maasrot 4:5
- Ch24 Olivet Discourse: "abomination of desolation" from Dan 9:27/11:31 via Antiochus IV
  as historical referent; Eusebius Eccl. Hist. 3.5.3 records Pella flight before 70 CE;
  cosmic signs language from Isa 13:10; 34:4; Joel 2:10 — not literal cosmology;
  "this generation" debate noted but not resolved
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "23": {
    "2": '<p>"The scribes and the Pharisees sit on Moses\' seat" (<em>epi tēs Mōuseōs kathedras ekathisan</em>) — the cathedra (chair of authority) was a literal object in synagogues: a stone seat near the Torah ark from which authoritative interpretation was delivered. Sitting to teach was the formal posture of rabbinic authority (cf. Luke 4:20; John 8:2). The phrase acknowledges that the Pharisees occupy a legitimate institutional position within the Torah-interpretation tradition that descends from Moses.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Do what they say but not what they do" — a startling acknowledgment of institutional authority decoupled from personal exemplification. Jesus does not tell his disciples to ignore Pharisaic teaching in principle but to distinguish between authoritative transmission of Torah content and the lived hypocrisy that undermines it. This verse resists any simple reading of the Woes as anti-Pharisaic wholesale: the issue is practice, not office.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"They tie up heavy burdens (<em>phortia barea</em>) and lay them on people\'s shoulders, but they themselves are not willing to move them with their finger" — the "heavy burdens" refer to the halakhic expansions of the oral tradition, the "fence around the Torah" (m. Avot 1:1 commands: "Make a fence around the Torah"). The Mishnah and Talmud later codified hundreds of specific applications: 39 categories of Sabbath-prohibited work, elaborate purity rules, tithing regulations. The critique is not that rules exist but that the teachers impose without enabling — they do not themselves bear the weight they place on others.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Phylacteries (<em>phylaktēria</em>) are the Greek name for the Jewish <em>tefillin</em> — small black leather boxes containing four Torah passages (Exod 13:1-10; 13:11-16; Deut 6:4-9; 11:13-21) bound on the left arm and forehead during morning weekday prayer, fulfilling Deut 6:8 literally. "Broad phylacteries" (<em>platynousin</em>) means making the boxes larger as a visible display of piety. The fringes (<em>kraspeda</em>) are the <em>tzitzit</em> — tassels required by Num 15:38-40 and Deut 22:12 on the four corners of a garment, intended to be visible reminders of the commandments. Lengthening them was another form of public piety display.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The place of honor at banquets (<em>prōtoklisian</em>) is the reclining couch at the top of the symposium arrangement, nearest the host. In the Greek and Roman banquet tradition this position was the highest honor, its occupant identifiable to all present. The front seat in synagogues (<em>prōtokathedral</em>) was the bench facing the congregation (and facing toward Jerusalem), reserved for senior members and teachers. Both positions made social rank visible and permanent throughout the gathering.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Greetings in the marketplaces and the title "Rabbi" (<em>hrabbi</em>) — the honorific title "Rabbi" (literally "my great one") was in process of formalization during the first century; it became the standard designation for ordained teachers after 70 CE. Public greeting in the <em>agora</em> was a performance of social rank: the higher-status person acknowledged by greetings and titles confirmed community recognition of their position. The desire for such greetings is a desire for public status-validation.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"But you are not to be called rabbi, for you have one teacher, and you are all brothers" — the horizontal community structure Jesus commands rejects the vertical title-hierarchy of rabbinic Judaism. "One teacher" (<em>heis estin hymon ho didaskalos</em>) — Jesus himself occupies the teaching role that the rabbinic chain of transmission claimed to occupy. "All brothers" (<em>pantes de hymeis adelphoi este</em>) collapses the hierarchical teacher-student distinction into a sibling relationship under one Father.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"And call no one your father on earth, for you have one Father, who is in heaven" — the prohibition on "Father" as a religious title prevents the kind of filial piety relationship that created binding dependence on human teachers. In the rabbinic tradition, one\'s teacher was spoken of in terms that paralleled one\'s father — transmission of Torah created a quasi-paternal relationship. Jesus reserves this relationship to God alone, preventing any human teacher from claiming the covenant-father role.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Neither be called instructors (<em>kathēgētai</em>), for you have one instructor, the Christ" — the Greek <em>kathēgētēs</em> designates a guide or leader as well as a teacher. All three prohibited titles (rabbi, father, instructor) are titles that claim interpretive authority over others. Jesus\'s prohibition restructures the community around his own authority rather than establishing a new human hierarchy to replace the Pharisaic one.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"The greatest among you shall be your servant" — the honor-reversal principle of 20:26-27 is restated here in the context of the leadership critique. The greatest (in terms of kingdom status) is determined by service rendered, not titles held. The Pharisees accumulate titles; the kingdom community accumulates service. The two economies of status are structurally incompatible.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Whoever exalts himself will be humbled, and whoever humbles himself will be exalted" — an eschatological inversion principle that appears as a general law in both OT and Jewish wisdom tradition (Prov 29:23; Ezek 21:26; Job 22:29; 1QH 15:15). Jesus frames it as the operating logic of the kingdom: the divine response to human self-promotion is diminishment; to self-lowering, elevation. The Woes that follow illustrate the consequences of the scribes and Pharisees\' self-exaltation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The first Woe: "You shut the kingdom of heaven in people\'s faces" — the scribes and Pharisees as gatekeepers who deny entry through their own unbelief and block others from entering. The word <em>kleiete</em> (you lock, you shut) is the same root used in Matt 16:19 where Peter receives the keys of the kingdom. Those who should be door-openers have become door-closers. The woe (<em>ouai</em>) is the prophetic lament-curse: a declaration of grief and judgment simultaneously.</p>',
    "14": '<p>This verse ("you devour widows\' houses and for a pretense make long prayers") is absent from the earliest manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and is generally considered a scribal insertion from Mark 12:40 and Luke 20:47. It does not appear in the best manuscript tradition of Matthew and is omitted from modern critical editions. The verse-numbering gap in modern translations reflects its absence.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The second Woe: "You travel across sea and land to make a single proselyte, and when he becomes a proselyte, you make him twice as much a child of hell as yourselves" — the Pharisaic proselytizing mission is attested in Roman sources (Horace, Sat. 1.4.143; Roman expulsion of Jews 139 BCE partly for proselytizing). The charge is not that making converts is wrong but that the proselyte is formed in the teachers\' defects, inheriting their distorted piety and becoming an intensified version of it.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The third Woe (vv. 16-22) targets oath-taking distinctions in halakhic debate. "Blind guides (<em>hodēgoi typhloi</em>) who say, \'If anyone swears by the temple, it is nothing, but if anyone swears by the gold of the temple, he is bound by his oath\'" — the Mishnah tractate <em>Nedarim</em> and <em>Shevuot</em> contain extensive discussions about which oaths are binding and which can be released. Swearing by an object that can be given to the temple vs. by the temple itself created a legal distinction between binding and non-binding vows.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"You blind fools! For which is greater, the gold or the temple that has made the gold sacred?" — the logical critique of halakhic oath distinctions is that they reverse the order of sanctity. The gold derives its sacred status from the temple (the context of consecration), not the other way around. To treat the consecrating object (gold) as more binding than the consecrating context (temple) is to confuse derivative and primary sanctity.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"And you say, \'If anyone swears by the altar, it is nothing, but if anyone swears by the gift that is on the altar, he is bound by his oath\'" — a parallel oath distinction: the altar vs. the sacrifice on it. The same logical problem arises: the sacrifice derives its sacred status from the altar of consecration. The halakhic ruling has confused what makes something holy with the holy thing itself.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"You blind men! For which is greater, the gift or the altar that makes the gift sacred?" — the repetition of the blind-fools charge with the same logical structure as v.17 reinforces the critique: this is not an isolated error but a pattern of reasoning that consistently gets the hierarchy of sanctity backwards. The "blind" epithet recurs throughout the Woes (v.16, 17, 19, 24, 26) as the defining diagnosis.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Therefore, whoever swears by the altar swears by it and by everything on it" — Jesus collapses the halakhic distinction by showing that swearing by the altar necessarily includes the gift on it (since the altar\'s purpose is the sacrifice) and vice versa. Any meaningful oath by the altar implicates the full sacrificial complex. The attempt to use definitional distinctions to escape the weight of oaths is exposed as illogical.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"And whoever swears by the temple swears by it and by him who dwells in it" — the temple is YHWH\'s dwelling place (1 Kgs 8:10-13; Ezek 43:4-7); any oath by the temple necessarily invokes the one who inhabits it. The attempt to swear by the building while avoiding the divine presence it houses is incoherent: the building\'s entire significance derives from the divine indwelling.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"And whoever swears by heaven swears by the throne of God and by him who sits upon it" — the escalation to heaven makes the point absolutely: all oaths ultimately invoke God, regardless of what object is nominally named. No human-devised distinction can create an oath that does not implicate divine witness. The elaborate halakhic distinctions about oath-bindingness are shown to be not just logically confused but theologically evasive.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The fourth Woe: "You tithe mint and dill and cummin, and have neglected the weightier matters of the law: justice and mercy and faithfulness" — the Mishnah tractate <em>Maasrot</em> (4:5) explicitly lists herbs including mint (<em>mentha</em>), dill (<em>anethon</em>), and cummin (<em>kuminon</em>) as subject to tithe. Tithing garden herbs to the last leaf was technically correct Torah-observance (Lev 27:30 requires tithing "everything from the land"). The critique is not that this is wrong but that "the weightier matters of the law" — the prophetic priorities of justice (<em>mishpat</em>), mercy (<em>chesed</em>), and faithfulness (<em>emunah</em>) — have been squeezed out by the focus on small-scale technical compliance.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"You blind guides, straining out a gnat and swallowing a camel!" — gnats (<em>kōnōpes</em>) were Levitically impure creatures (Lev 11:41-42) that could contaminate wine if consumed. Straining wine through a cloth to remove gnats was a common purity practice. The camel (<em>kamēlos</em>) is the largest Levitically impure animal (Lev 11:4). The hyperbole is deliberate and comic: the contrast between the smallest and largest impure creature perfectly captures the disproportionality of Pharisaic purity-focus — meticulous about tiny impurities while consuming massive ones.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The fifth Woe: "You clean the outside of the cup and the plate, but inside they are full of greed and self-indulgence" — the purity of vessels was an elaborate concern in rabbinic law: the Mishnah tractate <em>Kelim</em> (Vessels) contains thirty chapters addressing the impurity-susceptibility of various containers based on material, shape, and use. The cup that is ritually pure on the outside while full of extortion is a precise image of formal religious compliance masking moral corruption.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"First clean the inside of the cup and the plate, that the outside also may be clean" — the metaphor addresses priorities in the order of moral transformation: the source of action (the interior character) must be addressed before external behavior can be genuinely changed. External purity practice derived from internal greed produces only a surface result. The reversal of the typical ritual focus (outside → inside) mirrors the reversal of the typical honor economy (visible → hidden).</p>',
    "27": '<p>The sixth Woe: "You are like whitewashed tombs, which outwardly appear beautiful, but within are full of dead people\'s bones and all uncleanness" — tombs were whitewashed with lime before Passover (m. Shekalim 1:1; m. Maasrot Sheni 5:1; b. Moed Katan 5a) specifically to warn pilgrims traveling to Jerusalem: contact with a grave or its immediate area caused seven days of corpse-impurity (Num 19:16), which would prevent participation in the Passover. The whitewash made graves visible and beautiful — a public safety marker that also beautified dangerous defilement. The image is precise: the Pharisees\' public appearance is both beautiful and specifically designed to warn others away from the defilement within.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Outwardly you appear righteous to others, but within you are full of hypocrisy and lawlessness" (<em>anomias</em>) — the diagnosis is not that the Pharisees are outwardly wicked but that their outward righteousness is a performance divorced from interior reality. <em>Hypocrisis</em> in Greek originally meant stage-acting (playing a role). The actors wear the mask of righteousness; inside is the opposite. The antithesis between external appearance and internal reality is the structural center of the Woes.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The seventh Woe: "You build the tombs of the prophets and decorate the monuments of the righteous" — the veneration of prophets\' tombs was widespread in Second Temple Judaism. Josephus refers to commemorative structures for the Maccabean family (<em>Ant.</em> 13.211); the Tomb of Zechariah in the Kidron Valley (traditionally dated to the Second Temple period) and similar monumental tomb-structures were religious sites. The building and decorating of such tombs was an act of piety toward those who died for faithfulness to God — or so it appeared.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"And you say, \'If we had lived in the days of our fathers, we would not have taken part with them in shedding the blood of the prophets\'" — the self-distancing from the fathers who killed the prophets is both sincere (they genuinely believe they would have acted differently) and ironic (they are in the act of plotting to kill Jesus). The historical distance that allows comfortable condemnation of the fathers does not translate into behavioral change when the living prophetic word confronts them directly.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Thus you witness against yourselves that you are sons of those who murdered the prophets" — the testimony is their own statement: by identifying themselves as the children of the prophet-killers, they claim the lineage. In the deuteronomistic tradition, Israel\'s characteristic sin is the rejection and killing of prophets (2 Chr 36:15-16; Neh 9:26; Jer 7:25-26). To claim descent from that tradition is to claim participation in it.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"Fill up, then, the measure of your fathers" (<em>plērōsate to metron tōn paterōn hymōn</em>) — this ironic command anticipates the completion of the pattern: Jesus\' death will fill the measure of prophet-rejection that began with Abel. The "measure" (<em>metron</em>) is a capacity that has been building through generations and will be filled by the act they are about to commit.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"You serpents, you brood of vipers, how are you to escape being sentenced to hell?" — the "brood of vipers" epithet connects to John the Baptist\'s identical charge (3:7), placing the Pharisees in a continuous line of covenant resistance that the Baptist had already identified. The rhetorical question — "how are you to escape?" — is unanswerable given the preceding analysis: they are repeating the pattern of their fathers with full self-awareness.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Therefore I send you prophets and wise men and scribes, some of whom you will kill and crucify, and some you will flog in your synagogues and persecute from town to town" — Jesus identifies himself as the sender of God\'s messengers, claiming the divine role in the prophetic-martyrdom tradition. The list of measures (killing, crucifying, flogging, persecuting) describes the treatment of the early Christian community documented in Acts and Paul\'s letters, making this a prospective judgment-oracle on the community\'s response to the apostolic mission.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"So that on you may come all the righteous blood shed on earth, from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah the son of Berechiah, whom you murdered between the sanctuary and the altar" — the span from Abel (Gen 4:8, the first murder in Scripture) to Zechariah covers the full Hebrew canon: in the Hebrew Bible\'s order, Genesis is the first book and Chronicles the last; Zechariah son of Jehoiada was killed "in the court of the house of the LORD" (2 Chr 24:21), making him the last martyr recorded in the canon. This is a merism — all prophetic blood from first to last in the biblical narrative.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, all these things will come upon this generation" — the judgment announced is not deferred to the eschaton but specified as falling on "this generation" (<em>tautēn tēn genean</em>). This language, used consistently in Matthew (12:39, 41-42; 17:17; 23:36; 24:34), refers to the contemporaries of Jesus who are rejecting his ministry. The Woes culminate in a judgment-oracle whose realization is imminent.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to it! How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings, and you were not willing!" — the "gathering under wings" image for divine protection occurs throughout the Psalms (17:8; 36:7; 57:1; 61:4; 91:4) and Ruth 2:12 ("under whose wings you have come to take refuge"). The image of YHWH as a bird gathering Israel is maternal and tender; its frustration — "you were not willing" (<em>ouk ēthelēsate</em>) — is the climactic statement of Israel\'s covenant resistance.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"See, your house is left to you desolate" (<em>aphietai hymin ho oikos hymōn erēmos</em>) — the "house" is the temple. The pronouncement echoes Jeremiah\'s Temple Sermon (Jer 7:1-15), where YHWH threatens to abandon the temple as he abandoned Shiloh, and Ezekiel\'s vision of the divine glory departing from the temple (Ezek 8-11). "Your house" rather than "my house" signals the withdrawal of divine ownership: the temple has reverted to being merely Israel\'s building, no longer YHWH\'s dwelling.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"For I tell you, you will not see me again, until you say, \'Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord\'" — the citation of Ps 118:26 (the messianic acclamation of the triumphal entry, 21:9) frames the departure and future return as a bracket around a period of absence. Jesus\' departure from the temple precincts is presented as a hiatus, not a final end; the messianic acclamation will be heard again at the parousia. The lament closes with a conditional future, not despair.</p>'
  },
  "24": {
    "2": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, there will not be left here one stone upon another that will not be thrown down" — the prediction of the temple\'s total destruction was fulfilled by the Roman legions under Titus in August 70 CE. Josephus describes the systematic demolition of the outer walls, the burning of the colonnades, and the Roman soldiers dismantling stones to retrieve melted gold from the treasury (<em>War</em> 6.250, 354-408). The archaeological remains visible today confirm the catastrophic scale: stones from the Herodian courses weighing hundreds of tons were toppled from the temple platform.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The disciples\' question conflates two events: "when will these things be?" (the temple\'s destruction) and "what will be the sign of your coming and of the end of the age?" The Mount of Olives, east of the temple across the Kidron Valley, provided a direct view of the temple complex — an appropriate setting for the discourse on its fate. The conflation of questions reflects a common Second Temple assumption: the destruction of Jerusalem and the arrival of the messianic age were expected to coincide.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"See that no one leads you astray" — the opening warning against deception sets the interpretive frame for the entire discourse. Messianic claimants were a recurring feature of first-century Jewish life. Josephus documents several: Theudas (ca. 44 CE, <em>Ant.</em> 20.97-99), the Egyptian prophet (ca. 56 CE, <em>Ant.</em> 20.169-171; <em>War</em> 2.261-263), and various figures during the Jewish-Roman War (66-70 CE) who promised divine deliverance at the last moment. The first sign of the end is not cosmic spectacle but messianic fraud.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"For many will come in my name, saying, \'I am the Christ\'" — the use of "in my name" suggests claimants who appeal to Jesus-like categories (the anointed one, the deliverer) rather than necessarily claiming to be Jesus himself. The proliferation of prophets and messianic figures in the decades leading to 70 CE is extensively documented in Josephus and provides the immediate historical context for this warning.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"You will hear of wars and rumors of wars" — the period from 30-70 CE was marked by successive crises: the assassination of Caligula (41 CE), the Claudian expulsions, Nero\'s instability (54-68 CE), the Year of the Four Emperors (69 CE), and continuous tension in Palestine between Jewish factions and Rome. "Rumors of wars" (<em>akoai polemōn</em>) — news traveling through the Mediterranean world created constant uncertainty. "But see that you are not alarmed, for this must take place, but the end is not yet" frames these events as necessary but not terminal.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Nation will rise against nation, and kingdom against kingdom, and there will be famines and earthquakes in various places" — the language of international conflict, famine, and earthquake is standard in OT prophetic judgment-announcements (Isa 19:2; 2 Chr 15:6) and Jewish apocalyptic literature (4 Ezra 13:31; 2 Bar. 70:8). A severe famine struck the eastern Mediterranean ca. 46-48 CE (Acts 11:28); significant earthquakes occurred throughout the period. These are "birth pangs" (<em>ōdinōn</em>, v.8) — the painful but not yet terminal signs of the age\'s transition.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"All these are but the beginning of the birth pains" (<em>archē ōdinōn</em>) — the metaphor of birth pangs for eschatological distress is pervasive in the prophets: Isa 13:8; 26:17-18; Jer 22:23; Mic 4:9-10; 1 Thess 5:3. The image acknowledges that the suffering is real and intense but also purposive — birth pangs are not random pain but the labor that precedes new life. The sufferings described are not the end but the beginning of the process leading to it.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Then they will deliver you up to tribulation and put you to death, and you will be hated by all nations for my name\'s sake" — the persecution described here corresponds to the experience of the early church documented in Acts (5:17-18; 6:12; 8:1-3; 12:1-5; 13:50) and Paul\'s letters (2 Cor 11:24-26; Phil 1:29-30). "Hated by all nations" (<em>hypo pantōn tōn ethnōn</em>) anticipates the Gentile as well as Jewish hostility that would mark the apostolic mission.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"And then many will fall away (<em>skandalisthēsontai polloi</em>) and betray one another and hate one another" — apostasy under persecution is a recurring concern in Matthew (13:20-21, the rocky soil that withers under tribulation; 13:41, the scandal-causing factors at the harvest). The internal community dissolution — mutual betrayal and hatred — represents a more insidious danger than external persecution. The word <em>skandalon</em> (stumbling block, offense) implies the shattering of community bonds under pressure.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"And many false prophets will arise and lead many astray" — false prophets are distinguished from false messiahs (v.5) and represent a distinct category of internal threat: those who claim prophetic authority within the community rather than messianic status. The early church\'s struggle to discern true from false prophecy is visible in 1 Cor 12-14, 1 Thess 5:19-22, 1 John 4:1-6, and the Didache (11-13), which contains elaborate tests for discerning genuine prophets.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"And because lawlessness (<em>anomia</em>) is increased, the love of many will grow cold" — <em>anomia</em> (lawlessness, violation of covenant order) is a specifically Matthean concern (7:23; 13:41; 24:12; 2 Thess 2:3). The cooling of love (<em>psychēsetai hē agapē</em>) as a result of external moral disorder describes a communal spiritual dynamic: when the surrounding culture\'s disintegration exceeds a threshold, the internal cohesion of the covenant community weakens under pressure. This is not inevitable but possible, warranting the preceding and following calls to watchfulness.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"But the one who endures to the end will be saved" (<em>ho de hypoménōn eis telos, houtos sōthēsetai</em>) — endurance (<em>hypomonē</em>) as the characteristic virtue of the persecuted community appears also in Matt 10:22 (an earlier form of this saying), Rev 13:10, and Rom 5:3-4. "To the end" (<em>eis telos</em>) may mean either to the end of one\'s life or to the end of the age; both senses are appropriate to the discourse\'s double horizon (Jerusalem in 70 CE and the parousia).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"And this gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed throughout the whole world as a testimony to all nations, and then the end will come" — the worldwide proclamation of the gospel is both a prerequisite and a sign. The missionary horizon of the Great Commission (28:18-20) is already present here: the end does not come until the nations have heard the testimony. In Paul\'s theology, the full number of Gentiles must come in before Israel\'s salvation (Rom 11:25-26). The geography of mission is an eschatological timetable.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"So when you see the abomination of desolation spoken of by the prophet Daniel, standing in the holy place (<em>let the reader understand</em>)" — the parenthetical appeal to the reader is a rare intrusion of the author\'s voice, signaling that the referent requires interpretive attention. The "abomination of desolation" (<em>bdelygma tēs erēmōseōs</em>) appears in Dan 9:27, 11:31, and 12:11, where it refers to Antiochus IV Epiphanes\' desecration of the Jerusalem temple in 167 BCE (setting up an altar to Zeus and sacrificing pigs). Jesus applies the term to a future event; in 70 CE the Roman military standards (<em>signa</em>) bearing the emperor\'s image were set up in the temple court and sacrifice offered to them.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains" — a practical escape instruction for inhabitants of Judea, consistent with the geography of the warning. In 66-68 CE, as the Jewish-Roman war escalated, Eusebius records (<em>Eccl. Hist.</em> 3.5.3) that the Jerusalem church received a divine oracle instructing them to flee to Pella in the Decapolis (east of the Jordan River) before the siege began. Whether or not Eusebius\'s account is accurate, the instruction to flee represents a break with the normal expectation of defending Jerusalem as YHWH\'s holy city.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Let the one who is on the housetop not go down to take what is in his house" — Palestinian houses had flat roofs accessible by external stairs; the roof was used for sleeping, storage, and daily activities. The warning is about urgency: do not delay by going inside to collect possessions. The same urgency applies to the person in the field. The advice mirrors Lot\'s escape from Sodom (Gen 19:17: "Flee for your life. Do not look back or stop anywhere in the valley").</p>',
    "18": '<p>"And let the one who is in the field not turn back to take his cloak" — the <em>himation</em> (outer cloak) was a significant piece of property, essential for warmth and with legal protections (Exod 22:26-27: a creditor must return a cloak by nightfall because it serves as a blanket). Leaving it behind signals extreme urgency: survival matters more than this valuable necessity. The specific details ground the warning in practical Judean peasant life.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"And alas for women who are pregnant and for those who are nursing infants in those days!" — pregnant and nursing mothers face the greatest physical vulnerability in conditions requiring rapid flight. This is not a theological statement but a concrete acknowledgment of human limitation. It is a lament, not a prediction of special punishment; it voices the sorrowful realism of the oracle, acknowledging that flight conditions will be devastating for the most physically vulnerable.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Pray that your flight may not be in winter or on a Sabbath" — winter travel in Judea was genuinely dangerous: the Jordan River could flood (Josh 3:15 notes that the Jordan overflows its banks in the spring flood season); mountain passes could be snow-covered; food procurement was more difficult. Sabbath flight created a halakhic dilemma: Sabbath travel was restricted to about one kilometer (the Sabbath day\'s journey, Acts 1:12). The Maccabean crisis produced a ruling (1 Macc 2:41) that self-defense was permitted on the Sabbath, but rapid evacuation of an entire community raised new questions.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"For then there will be great tribulation (<em>thlipsis megalē</em>), such as has not been from the beginning of the world until now, no, and never will be" — <em>thlipsis</em> is the standard apocalyptic term for eschatological distress (Dan 12:1 LXX: "a time of distress such as has never occurred since nations came into existence"). Josephus\'s account of the siege of Jerusalem (70 CE) describes conditions of extraordinary horror: famine, faction violence within the city, the death of over one million people (<em>War</em> 6.420), crucifixion of hundreds of prisoners daily outside the walls. Whether Josephus\'s numbers are exaggerated or not, the event was catastrophic.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"And if those days had not been cut short, no human being would be saved (<em>sōthēsetai pasa sarx</em>). But for the sake of the elect those days will be cut short" — "no human being would survive" (<em>pasa sarx</em> = all flesh) acknowledges the total-destruction potential of the Roman military campaign. "For the sake of the elect" (<em>dia tous eklektous</em>) — the divine limitation of the period of judgment is motivated by the presence of the covenant community within the zone of destruction. This is a theological application of the Abraham-Lot principle: divine judgment is moderated by the righteous who remain within it.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Then if anyone says to you, \'Look, here is the Christ!\' or \'There he is!\' do not believe it" — after describing the tribulation associated with the fall of Jerusalem, the discourse pivots back to the central warning against messianic fraud. False messiahs proliferated precisely in conditions of extreme distress: several messianic claimants appeared during the 66-70 CE war, including Simon bar Giora and John of Gischala, who presented themselves as deliverers. The conditional "if anyone says" acknowledges these will be compelling claims made in desperate circumstances.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"For false christs and false prophets will arise and perform great signs and wonders (<em>sēmeia megala kai terata</em>), so as to lead astray, if possible, even the elect" — the power of signs and wonders to validate claims to authority is acknowledged: these are not negligible frauds but convincing miracle-workers. Josephus describes prophets during the war who promised miraculous deliverance (<em>War</em> 6.285: a prophet led 6,000 to the temple porticos expecting divine rescue, where they were burned). The elect\'s potential deception ("if possible") acknowledges the threat without guaranteeing immunity through complacency.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"See, I have told you beforehand" (<em>idou proeirēka hymin</em>) — the prospective declaration creates a test: when the predicted events occur, their occurrence will confirm the reliability of Jesus\' word rather than destabilizing faith. This is the apologetic function of predictive prophecy within the discourse: the disciples\' encounter with tribulation, false prophets, and messianic fraud has been pre-announced, preventing it from functioning as evidence against Jesus\' authority.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"So, if they say to you, \'Look, he is in the wilderness\', do not go out. If they say, \'Look, he is in the inner rooms,\' do not believe it" — both locations have specific associations: wilderness was the standard staging ground for messianic movements (cf. Theudas\'s wilderness march, the Egyptian prophet\'s desert assembly). Inner rooms suggest a hidden, esoteric revelation available only to initiates. Both represent the opposite of the public, universal, unmistakable parousia that v.27 describes.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"For as the lightning comes from the east and shines as far as the west, so will be the coming (<em>parousia</em>) of the Son of Man" — <em>parousia</em> is the technical term for a royal or imperial visit (used in papyri for the arrival of the emperor or a governor in a city, requiring public preparation and greeting). The lightning image guarantees universality and immediacy: the parousia will be visible simultaneously everywhere, requiring no announcement, no travel to witness it. It is the opposite of the local, hidden manifestations warned against in v.26.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Wherever the corpse is, there the vultures will gather" — a proverbial saying about the inevitable convergence of predators and their prey (cf. Job 39:30; Luke 17:37). In the context of v.27, it functions as a secondary image of universality: just as vultures find the corpse wherever it lies with no human direction, the parousia will be self-locating and unmissable. The proverb may also carry judgment imagery: the Son of Man\'s arrival will inevitably find and converge on the place of judgment.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"Immediately after the tribulation of those days: the sun will be darkened, and the moon will not give its light, and the stars will fall from heaven, and the powers of the heavens will be shaken" — this is standard OT apocalyptic language for divine judgment and cosmic disruption, not a prediction of literal astronomical events. Isa 13:10 uses identical language for the fall of Babylon; Joel 2:10 for the Day of the LORD; Ezek 32:7 for Egypt\'s judgment; Amos 8:9 for Israel\'s judgment. The language signals a world-historical turning point of ultimate significance, described in the only vocabulary capable of conveying it.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"Then will appear in heaven the sign of the Son of Man, and then all the tribes of the earth will mourn, and they will see the Son of Man coming on the clouds of heaven with power and great glory" — Dan 7:13-14 provides the primary framework: the "one like a son of man" comes on the clouds to the Ancient of Days and receives dominion over all peoples. "All the tribes of the earth will mourn" (<em>kopsontai pasai hai phylai tēs gēs</em>) echoes Zech 12:10-14, where the tribes of Israel mourn over "the one they have pierced." Matthew universalizes: the mourning extends to all peoples.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"And he will send out his angels with a loud trumpet call, and they will gather his elect from the four winds, from one end of heaven to the other" — the great trumpet as eschatological signal appears in Isa 27:13 ("a great trumpet will sound") for the ingathering of exiles, Zech 9:14 (the divine warrior\'s trumpet at the end), and 1 Thess 4:16 (the trumpet of God at the resurrection). "From the four winds" echoes Ezek 37:9 (the four winds breathing life into the dry bones) and the Deuteronomy 30:4 promise of gathering Israel from the ends of the earth.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"From the fig tree learn its lesson: as soon as its branch becomes tender and puts out its leaves, you know that summer is near" — the fig tree as a seasonal calendar: in Palestine the fig tree is one of the last to leaf out in spring, making its leafing a reliable indicator that summer is imminent. The fig tree as a symbol of Israel (as in the cursing of 21:19) may carry additional resonance, but the primary point is about reading observable signs for timing. The disciples are to read the signs Jesus has described with the same reliable skill a farmer uses to read seasonal indicators.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"So also, when you see all these things, you know that he is near, at the very gates" — "all these things" (<em>panta tauta</em>) refers to the signs described in vv. 4-28: tribulation, false prophets, cosmic signs. When these converge, the event they signal is "at the very gates" (<em>epi thyrais</em>) — the idiom for immediate imminence (cf. Jas 5:9: "the Judge is standing at the very door"). The language of proximity is temporal, not spatial.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, this generation will not pass away until all these things take place" — one of the most debated verses in the Gospels. Three main readings: (1) "this generation" refers to Jesus\' contemporaries, and "all these things" refers to the destruction of Jerusalem and its immediate signs (fulfilled in 70 CE); (2) "generation" means the Jewish people, who will persist until the eschatological events; (3) "this generation" refers to the final generation that witnesses the signs described. The first reading has the strongest linguistic support for <em>genea</em>; the interpretation of "all these things" is the crux of the debate.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away" — the eschatological permanence of Jesus\' words is grounded in their contrast with the created order. That heaven and earth are temporary is an OT assumption (Isa 51:6; Ps 102:25-26) confirmed in the NT (2 Pet 3:10-12; Rev 21:1). Against this background, the permanence of Jesus\' words constitutes a claim to the kind of authority that only divine speech possesses — the word that stands when the cosmos changes.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"But concerning that day and hour no one knows, not even the angels of heaven, nor the Son, but the Father only" — the limitation of knowledge "not even the Son" (<em>oud\' ho huios</em>) is a remarkable Christological statement. In Jewish apocalyptic literature, angels were frequently given specialized eschatological knowledge (Dan 8-12). To say that the Son does not know what the Father knows raises the question of how knowledge is distributed within the Godhead — a question that occupied later trinitarian theology. The practical purpose of the statement is to prevent any claim to calculate the timing of the parousia.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"For as were the days of Noah, so will be the coming of the Son of Man" — the Noah typology draws on Gen 6-7. The comparison is not to the flood\'s violence but to the normalcy of life before it: eating, drinking, marrying. The people of Noah\'s generation did not recognize the coming judgment because their ordinary life gave no indication of it. The parousia will similarly arrive within the normal flow of human life — not after a period of obvious signs that allows preparation, but suddenly, within everyday activity.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"For as in those days before the flood they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, until the day when Noah entered the ark" — the four activities (eating, drinking, marrying, giving in marriage) are the basic activities of social life: feeding oneself and one\'s household, and establishing kinship bonds. None of them is wicked in itself; the problem is their exclusivity — all attention was devoted to the ordinary while the extraordinary approached. The ark was being built in plain sight (Gen 6:13-22) and Noah was a "preacher of righteousness" (2 Pet 2:5), yet the warning went unheeded.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"And they were unaware until the flood came and swept them all away, so will be the coming of the Son of Man" — the key word is "unaware" (<em>ouk egnōsan</em>): they did not know, in the sense of not recognizing or taking seriously what was happening. The comparison is specifically about this epistemological failure — the failure to understand the meaning of what they were witnessing (Noah\'s preaching, the ark\'s construction). The disciples who hear Jesus\' discourse are being given knowledge that Noah\'s contemporaries lacked; their responsibility to watch is correspondingly greater.</p>',
    "40": '<p>"Then two men will be in the field; one will be taken and one left" — the "taking" and "leaving" in this context likely refers to the gathering of the elect (v.31) and the separation of judgment, consistent with the harvest parables (13:30, 49). The imagery is of selective action within the normal activities of agricultural work and domestic activity. The identity of who is taken and who is left is not specified in terms of visible characteristics — both are doing the same work, which underscores the unpredictability of the moment.</p>',
    "41": '<p>"Two women will be grinding at the mill; one will be taken and one left" — hand grinding (using the rotary quern or saddle quern) was exclusively women\'s work in ancient Palestinian households. Two women grinding together was a normal domestic scene. The imagery again emphasizes the penetration of the eschatological event into the most ordinary and private of domestic settings: the parousia does not occur in a special religious location but in the field and the kitchen. The pattern of two-in-ordinary-activity applies across gender.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"Therefore, stay awake (<em>grēgoreite</em>), for you do not know on what day your Lord is coming" — <em>grēgorein</em> (to stay awake, to watch) is the characteristic virtue of the eschatologically prepared community. The ignorance of timing (v.36) is not a reason for passivity but for continuous readiness. The imperative connects to the series of parables that follows (the thief, the faithful servant, the ten virgins, the talents) — all of which are parables about what sustained readiness looks like in practice.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"But know this, that if the master of the house had known in what part of the night the thief was coming, he would have stayed awake and would not have let his house be broken into" — the thief image is not a moral comparison (Jesus is not like a thief in character) but a comparison of unexpectedness. The householder\'s failure is not culpable but illustrates the logic of preparedness: if the timing were known, the response would be obvious. Since it is unknown, continuous readiness is the only rational response.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"Therefore you also must be ready, for the Son of Man is coming at an hour you do not expect" (<em>ou dokeiete hōra</em>) — "at an hour you do not expect" reverses normal strategic calculation. If you knew the time, you would prepare then. But since the parousia comes precisely when not expected, the only adequate preparation is constant preparedness. The eschatological logic of the discourse reaches its practical conclusion: readiness cannot be deferred to a calculated time because the time cannot be calculated.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"Who then is the faithful and wise servant (<em>doulos</em>), whom his master has set over his household, to give them their food at the proper time?" — the parable of the two servants grounds the abstract call to watchfulness in a concrete social scenario. A slave manager (<em>doulos</em>) left in charge of the master\'s household during an absence had both opportunity and temptation: he could either faithfully execute his responsibilities or exploit the master\'s absence. The household management role was a real position in ancient domestic economies; such slave-managers (oikonomoi) had considerable delegated authority.</p>',
    "46": '<p>"Blessed is that servant whom his master will find so doing when he comes" — the blessing is for consistent performance of assigned duties, not for special readiness behaviors adopted near the master\'s return. The faithful servant is not on alert for the master\'s return; he is simply doing what the master assigned. The beatitude form (<em>makarios</em>) connects to the Beatitudes of the Sermon on the Mount: this is kingdom-character, not merely a practical virtue.</p>',
    "47": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, he will set him over all his possessions" — the faithful servant\'s reward is an expansion of responsibility and trust: from managing the household to managing "all his possessions" (<em>epi pasi tois hyparchousin autou</em>). This is the eschatological logic of stewardship: faithfulness in the assigned task during the master\'s absence is vindicated and amplified at the master\'s return. The parable of the talents (25:14-30) will develop this principle further.</p>',
    "48": '<p>"But if that wicked servant says to himself, \'My master is delayed\'" (<em>chronizei mou ho kyrios</em>) — the delay of the parousia is the wicked servant\'s premise for abuse. The word <em>chronizei</em> (delays, takes a long time) suggests not a specific timeline but the open-ended extension of the master\'s absence. The psychological move — assuming the absence is extended enough to act with impunity — is the spiritual failure being diagnosed. The delay of the parousia is a pastoral and theological issue in the NT communities (2 Pet 3:3-4; 1 Thess 5:1-11).</p>',
    "49": '<p>"And begins to beat his fellow servants and eats and drinks with drunkards" — the wicked servant\'s conduct combines abuse of those under his authority and dissipation. "Beat his fellow servants" (<em>synduolus autou</em> — his co-slaves) violates the sibling solidarity of the servant community. Eating and drinking with drunkards represents the abandonment of the master\'s household norms for the entertainments of the surrounding world. Both behaviors are enabled by the perceived absence of accountability.</p>',
    "50": '<p>"The master of that servant will come on a day when he does not expect him and at an hour he does not know" — the irony is precise: the servant who calculated that the master\'s delay gave him freedom to act abusively is caught precisely because of the unpredictability he assumed would protect him. The timing of the master\'s arrival (unexpected day, unknown hour) echoes the v.44 warning about the Son of Man. The parable is an illustration of the very principle it teaches.</p>',
    "51": '<p>"And will cut him in pieces and put him with the hypocrites. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth" — <em>dichotomēsei auton</em> (will cut him in two) is a severe judgment image; "cut in pieces" may be hyperbolic for severe punishment or may echo the literal dismemberment penalties of some ancient legal systems. "With the hypocrites" (<em>meta tōn hypokritōn</em>) connects back to the Woes of ch. 23: the unfaithful servant who performs faithfulness while the master is absent but abandons it when accountability is suspended is precisely the hypocrite. "Weeping and gnashing of teeth" is Matthew\'s recurring eschatological judgment formula (8:12; 13:42, 50; 22:13; 25:30).</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew')
